article.description:
Vicky Bullett's 3-pointer with 1:59 remaining broke a tie and lifted the Washington Mystics to a come-from-behind
56-55 win over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday.
article.headline: Short-handed Mystics refuse to cave in

images.name: Jones_Asjha 020630 inline
images.caption: Washington's Asjha Jones looks to pass when faced with the defense of Charlotte's Andrea Stinson. Jones did get loose though to lead all scorers with 16 points.

article.linkText: Mystics rally to beat Sting despite missing Holdsclaw
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vicky Bullett's 3-pointer with 1:59 remaining
broke a tie and lifted the Washington Mystics to a come-from-behind
56-55 win over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday.

<photo1>

	   Playing without league-leading scorer Chamique Holdsclaw, the
Mystics rallied from a 16-point first-half deficit to win their
seventh consecutive home game.

	   "I looked up and there were four seconds left (on the shot
clock). With four seconds, there's not much you can do. I threw up
a Hail Mary, and it went in,'' Bullett said.

	   After Charlotte's Dawn Staley hit a jumper to start the second
half for a 38-24 lead, the Mystics outscored the Sting 32-17. Ashja
Jones scored 14 of her career-high 16 points in the second half,
including a layup with 4:10 remaining that gave Washington (11-4)
its first lead since 8-6.

	   "It was disappointing to lose our focus,'' Sting coach Anne
Donovan said. "We turned the ball over 18 times. It's tough to win
when you turn the ball over 18 times.

	   Jones led Washington with 16 points, while Bullett added 14.
Andrea Stinson led Charlotte (6-6) with 14 points, including a
first-half layup that gave Charlotte its largest lead, 36-20.

	   Jones' 10 points -- including four straight baskets -- cut the
Sting lead to 46-45 with 10:51 remaining. Staley's jumper, two free
throws by Tonya Edwards and a layup by Summer Erb increased
Charlotte's lead to 52-45. But Jones' jumper, a layup by Murriel
Page and a layup by Bullett brought the Mystics back to one, 52-51.
It was 53-53 when Bullett hit the winning 3-pointer.

	   Before the game, Washington placed Holdsclaw on the injured list
with a sprained left ankle. Holdsclaw, injured in a game at
Portland on June 28, must miss at least three games. She leads the
WNBA in scoring average with 19.9 points per game and is second in
rebounds with 11.8 per game.

	   "Everyone just has to do a little more,'' Jones said. "You
don't have to do everything. When she gets back, it'll give our
team a big lift.''
